<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEBushman200592–94-6"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBushman200592–94_6-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFBushman2005">Bushman 2005</a>, pp.&#160;92–94.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTESoutherton2004xv-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTESoutherton2004xv_7-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFSoutherton2004">Southerton 2004</a>, p.&#160;xv. "Anthropologists and archaeologists, including some Mormons and former Mormons, have discovered little to support the existence of [Book of Mormon] civilizations. Over a period of 150 years, as scholars have seriously studied Native American cultures and prehistory, evidence of a Christian civilization in the Americas has eluded the specialists... These [Mesoamerican] cultures lack any trace of Hebrew or Egyptian writing, metallurgy, or the Old World domesticated animals and plants described in the Book of Mormon."</span>
</li>
