<li id="cite_note-117"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-117">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFRidenhour" class="citation book cs1">Ridenhour, Lynn. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.centerplace.org/library/bofm/baptistversionofbofm.htm"><i>The Baptist Version of the Book of Mormon</i></a>. WinePress Publishing &#8211; via CenterPlace.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Baptist+Version+of+the+Book+of+Mormon&amp;rft.pub=WinePress+Publishing&amp;rft.aulast=Ridenhour&amp;rft.aufirst=Lynn&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.centerplace.org%2Flibrary%2Fbofm%2Fbaptistversionofbofm.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABook+of+Mormon" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-:21-118"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-:21_118-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-:21_118-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-:21_118-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFReynolds2020" class="citation journal cs1">Reynolds, Noel B. (2020). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://rsc.byu.edu/vol-21-no-1-2020/plan-salvation-book-mormon#_edn4">"The Plan of Salvation and the Book of Mormon"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Religious_Educator" class="mw-redirect" title="Religious Educator">Religious Educator</a></i>. <b>21</b> (1): 30–53. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210601072717/https://rsc.byu.edu/vol-21-no-1-2020/plan-salvation-book-mormon">Archived</a> from the original on June 1, 2021.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Religious+Educator&amp;rft.atitle=The+Plan+of+Salvation+and+the+Book+of+Mormon&amp;rft.volume=21&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=30-53&amp;rft.date=2020&amp;rft.aulast=Reynolds&amp;rft.aufirst=Noel+B.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Frsc.byu.edu%2Fvol-21-no-1-2020%2Fplan-salvation-book-mormon%23_edn4&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABook+of+Mormon" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTECrossLivingstone1997597-119"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTECrossLivingstone1997597_119-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFCrossLivingstone1997">Cross &amp; Livingstone 1997</a>, p.&#160;597. "[A]ll human life has been radically altered for the worse, so that its actual state is very different from that purposed for it by the Creator."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-120"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-120">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFCoviello2019">Coviello (2019</a>, p.&#160;8) summarizes, "bodies are not the seats of wickedness or Pauline corruption but something else entirely: the vehicles for exaltation... As the Book of Mormon observed, 'men are, that they might have joy.'"

The Book of Mormon reference is to <a href="/wiki/Second_Nephi" title="Second Nephi">2 Nephi</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/2?lang=eng&amp;id=22-25#p22">2:22&#8211;25</a>: "And now, behold, if Adam had not transgressed he would not have fallen, but he would have remained in the garden of Eden... And they would have had no children; wherefore they would have remained in a state of innocence, having no joy, for they knew no misery; doing no good, for they knew no sin... all things have been done in the wisdom of him who knoweth all things. Adam fell that men might be; and men are, that they might have joy."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEGivens2002217–219-121"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGivens2002217–219_121-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFGivens2002">Givens 2002</a>, pp.&#160;217–219.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEGivens2002219–220-122"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGivens2002219–220_122-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFGivens2002">Givens 2002</a>, pp.&#160;219–220. Givens refers to Nephi's encounter with Laban in which he is "constrained by the spirit" and to Enos's back-and-forth with the Lord as two examples of "conversational revelation" (1 Nephi 4:10–13; Enos 1:3–17).</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEGivens2002218–221-123"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGivens2002218–221_123-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFGivens2002">Givens 2002</a>, pp.&#160;218–221.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEGivens2002221–224-124"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGivens2002221–224_124-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFGivens2002">Givens 2002</a>, pp.&#160;221–224.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEGivens2002228-125"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGivens2002228_125-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFGivens2002">Givens 2002</a>, p.&#160;228.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-126"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-126">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">"Christianity is centered on revelation, which contains within it a message ("good news") meant for the believer. Given this message, what is important is the <i>content</i> of revelation, while scripture is usually regarded as a mere means of transmission" in <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFBiderman1995" class="citation book cs1">Biderman, Shlomo (1995). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=sb4nAAAAYAAJ"><i>Scripture and Knowledge: An Essay on Religious Epistemology</i></a>. <a href="/wiki/Brill_Publishers" title="Brill Publishers">Brill</a>. p.&#160;11. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9789004378919" title="Special:BookSources/9789004378919"><bdi>9789004378919</bdi></a>;</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Scripture+and+Knowledge%3A+An+Essay+on+Religious+Epistemology&amp;rft.pages=11&amp;rft.pub=Brill&amp;rft.date=1995&amp;rft.isbn=9789004378919&amp;rft.aulast=Biderman&amp;rft.aufirst=Shlomo&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dsb4nAAAAYAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABook+of+Mormon" class="Z3988"></span> <a href="#CITEREFCrossLivingstone1997">Cross &amp; Livingstone 1997</a>, p.&#160;1392: "[T]he <i>corpus</i> of truth about Himself which God discloses to us"; <a href="#CITEREFGivens2002">Givens 2002</a>, p.&#160;226: "We may contrast these examples with Shlomo Biderman's assertion .... In the Book of Mormon, what is important is not one ultimate Truth it embodies, but rather the ever-present reality of revelation it depicts".</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEGivens2002225-127"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGivens2002225_127-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFGivens2002">Givens 2002</a>, p.&#160;225.</span>
